## State Management

### Keep It Local

For prototypes, prefer `useState` and `useReducer`. Avoid global state libraries (Redux, Zustand) unless the prototype specifically demonstrates cross-screen state behavior.

```tsx
// ✅ Local state with typed enum
type ViewState = 'loading' | 'error' | 'empty' | 'populated';
const [viewState, setViewState] = useState<ViewState>('loading');
```

### Loading States — Skeleton, Not Spinner

```tsx
// ✅ Skeleton screen pattern
const SkeletonLine = ({ width = '100%', height = 16 }: { width?: string | number, height?: number }) => (
  <div style={{
    width,
    height,
    borderRadius: 'var(--radius-xs)',
    backgroundColor: 'var(--bg-tertiary)',
    // Pulse animation — respect prefers-reduced-motion
    animation: 'pulse 1.5s ease-in-out infinite',
  }} />
);
```

### Error States

Error components must answer: what happened, why, what to do next.

```tsx
// ✅ Error state pattern
<div style={{ ... }}>
  <p style={{ color: 'var(--color-negative)', fontWeight: [WEIGHT] }}>
    {errorMessage} {/* Specific, not "Something went wrong" */}
  </p>
  <button onClick={onRetry}>Try again</button>
</div>
```

